THOUGHT: I can see that in `formLCSSAImpl`, the worklist is populated with instructions that have uses outside the loop:

```cpp
for (Instruction &I : *BB) {
  // Reject two common cases fast: instructions with no uses (like stores)
  // and instructions with one use that is in the same block as this.
  if (I.use_empty() ||
      (I.hasOneUse() && I.user_back()->getParent() == BB &&
       !isa<PHINode>(I.user_back())))
    continue;

  // Tokens cannot be used in PHI nodes, so we skip over them.
  // We can run into tokens which are live out of a loop with catchswitch
  // instructions in Windows EH if the catchswitch has one catchpad which
  // is inside the loop and another which is not.
  if (I.getType()->isTokenTy())
    continue;

  Worklist.push_back(&I);
}
```

This adds all instructions that might have external uses to the worklist. Then `formLCSSAForInstructionsImpl` processes this worklist.

But the issue is that this approach doesn't handle dependency chains correctly. It only adds instructions that have direct external uses, not their operands.

The correct approach is to use a worklist algorithm that starts with instructions that have direct external uses, then adds their operands to the worklist if those operands are in the loop and don't already have LCSSA phis.

However, looking at the current implementation, it seems like it should work because it adds all instructions that might have external uses to the worklist, not just those with direct external uses.

The condition for adding to the worklist is:
- Not use_empty()
- Not (hasOneUse() and user in same block and user is not a PHI)

This means that `%load` should be added to the worklist because it has one use (`%add`) in the same block, but the user is not a PHI node, so it gets rejected by the optimization I removed earlier.

Ah! This confirms my initial hypothesis. The single-use optimization is indeed the problem.

When I removed the single-use optimization, I must have made a mistake in the sed command, which left the file in a broken state.

Let me fix the LCSSA.cpp file properly.

```bash
# Restore the backup and apply the fix correctly
cp /tmp/LCSSA.cpp.bak /llvm-autofix-deps/llvm/llvm/llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LCSSA.cpp
sed -i '419,421c\      if (I.use_empty())\        continue;' /llvm-autofix-deps/llvm/llvm/llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LCSSA.cpp
```

